____________________________________________________________________________________
PluGen - PluMA Plugin Generator
____________________________________________________________________________________

PluGen generates boilerplate code for PluMA plugins in multiple languages.

COMPILATION
-----------
To compile, run from the PluMA root directory:
    scons

Or compile just PluGen:
    g++ -o plugen main.cxx PluginGenerator.cxx JavaPluginGenerator.cxx

Note: Generated plugins will be placed in one of the following locations (in order):
1. ../plugins (relative to plugen)
2. PLUMA_PLUGIN_PATH directories (in order)

USAGE
-----
./plugen [OPTIONS] <PluginName> <command to run>

OPTIONS:
  --lang=<language>    Generate plugin in specified language
                       Supported: cpp (default), java

  --help, -h           Show usage information

ARGUMENTS:
  <PluginName>         Name of the new plugin (e.g., MyTool)
  <command to run>     Command to wrap (at least one word)
                       Use 'inputfile' and 'outputfile' as placeholders

EXAMPLES
--------

1. Generate a C++ plugin (default):
   ./plugen MyPlugin mytool -i inputfile -o outputfile

2. Generate a Java plugin:
   ./plugen --lang=java MyPlugin mytool -i inputfile -o outputfile

3. Plugin with optional parameters (use brackets):
   ./plugen MyPlugin mytool -i inputfile [ -v verbose ] -o outputfile

GENERATED FILES
---------------

C++ Plugins (--lang=cpp):
  plugins/MyPlugin/
  ├── MyPluginPlugin.h      # Header file
  ├── MyPluginPlugin.cpp    # Source file with input/run/output methods
  └── README.md             # Documentation

Java Plugins (--lang=java):
  plugins/MyPlugin/
  ├── MyPluginPlugin.java   # Java source with input/run/output methods
  └── README.md             # Documentation

  To compile Java plugins:
    cd plugins/MyPlugin
    javac MyPluginPlugin.java

PARAMETER FILE FORMAT
---------------------
Plugins expect a tab-delimited parameter file:

    param1    value1
    param2    value2
    inputpath /path/to/input

These parameters are accessible via:
- C++:  parameters["param1"]
- Java: parameters.get("param1")

